`★ Insight ─────────────────────────────────────`
**Why a 2-line fix works**: The root cause wasn't bad math — the HSB↔RGB conversion precision loss is inherent (continuous floats → 256 discrete integers → floats). The bug was *when* the conversion runs. `applyHexInput` fired on blur whenever the user clicked the mode toggle, even though the hex hadn't been edited. The guard `val.toUpperCase() === currentHex.toUpperCase()` short-circuits the reconversion, preserving the original HSB precision.

**Why drift stabilizes**: After one HSB→RGB→HSB round-trip, the HSB values land on a point that maps exactly back to the same integer RGB. So drift can't accumulate beyond the first cycle — but even one cycle shifts the internal state, which is why the guard matters.
`─────────────────────────────────────────────────`

